'''''Ninja Gaiden''''' is an [[action-adventure game]] developed by [[Team Ninja]] for the [[Xbox]] video game console. It went through five years of development before its release by [[Tecmo]] in 2004, and has been progressively enhanced with a number of expansion packs and two remakes, '''''Ninja Gaiden Black''''' and '''''Ninja Gaiden Sigma'''''. The game follows the fictional story of [[Ryu Hayabusa]], a [[ninja]], in his quest to recover a stolen sword and avenge the slaughter of his clan.

Inspired by the [[Ninja Gaiden#NES trilogy|1990s ''Ninja Gaiden'' series]] for the [[Nintendo Entertainment System]], the 2004 version is set in a re-imagined game world based on another Team Ninja creation, the [[Dead or Alive (series)|''Dead or Alive'']] series of [[fighting game]]s. Tecmo specifically targeted ''Ninja Gaiden'' at a non-[[Japanese people|Japanese]] audience, and despite difficulties in obtaining [[Video game content rating system|content ratings]] due to the game's graphic depictions of violence, it was generally well received, and 362,441 copies were sold in [[North America]] in the first month after its release. However, the game had to be censored for release in some regions, and Japanese sales were poor, with only 60,000 in the four months following its début.

Making use of the [[Xbox Live|Xbox's internet connectivity]], ''Ninja Gaiden'' was the focus of a series of [[Online game|online contests]] across North America, [[Europe]], and [[Japan]]. Record-breaking numbers of players took part, competing for places in the live final, which was held during the 2004 [[Tokyo Game Show]]. Noted for its fluid and responsive control system, technical merit, and the significant challenge it offers to even experienced gamers, ''Ninja Gaiden'' is regarded by several critics as one of the best and most difficult games ever made. Team Ninja continued to update the game after its release: two ''Hurricane Packs'' were made available for free download that added extra content, gameplay challenges, and [[game engine]] improvements. These were incorporated into a 2005 remake, entitled ''Ninja Gaiden Black'', that was regarded by the game's creator as the definitive version. Two years later, the game was [[ported]] to the [[PlayStation 3]] (PS3) [[game console]] and released as ''Ninja Gaiden Sigma''.

==Gameplay==
''Ninja Gaiden'' develops its narrative thread through the actions of its player-controlled protagonist, [[Ryu Hayabusa]]. Viewed from a [[Third-person shooter|third person]] over-the-shoulder perspective, in typical [[action-adventure game|action-adventure]] fashion Ryu starts the game with basic, low-level abilities and weapons that can be upgraded as he progresses, by discovering or buying items. In keeping with his [[ninja]] persona, his character can interact with the game environment to perform acrobatic feats, such as running along and jumping off walls, swinging from pole to pole, or running across water.<ref name="gsngrev">{{cite web
  | author = [[Greg Kasavin]]
  | title = Ninja Gaiden for Xbox Review
  | publisher = [[GameSpot]]
  | date = 2004-02-26
  | url = http://www.gamespot.com/xbox/action/ninjagaiden/review.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref>

The game world is made up of several distinct regions,<ref name="edge">{{cite journal
  | author = Edge staff
  | year = 2002
  | month = August
  | title = Inside... Tecmo
  | journal = [[Edge (magazine)|Edge]]
  | issue = 113
  | pages = pp. 51&ndash;55
  | publisher = [[Future plc|Future Publishing]]
  | location = Bath, England
  | issn = 1350-1593 }}
</ref> most of which are connected via the city of Tairon, which functions as a hub.{{Fact|date=August 2008}} Inspired by the mechanics of the ''[[The Legend of Zelda (series)|The Legend of Zelda]]'' video games, access to these regions is obtained by fighting enemies, finding keys, or solving puzzles.<ref name="gsngrev" /><ref name="sigpre">{{cite web
  | author = James Mielke
  | title = Previews: Ninja Gaiden Sigma
  | publisher = [[1UP.com]]
  | date = 2007-01-12
  | url = http://www.1up.com/do/previewPage?cId=3156377
  | accessdate = 2008-01-27 }}
</ref> To avoid disrupting its narrative flow, the game hides delays caused by loading a new area into memory by showing [[Cut scene|in game cut scenes]],<ref name="trend">{{cite web
  | author = Ron Burke
  | title = Ninja Gaiden
  | publisher = [[Gaming Trend]]
  | year = 2004
  | url = http://www.gamingtrend.com/Reviews/review/review.php?ReviewID=96
  | accessdate = 2008-02-03 }}
</ref> and [[Japanese dragon|Dragon]] [[bust (sculpture)|busts]] scattered throughout the regions provide the means to save player progress, permitting gameplay to be resumed at a later time.

In addition to the narrative Story Mode, subsequent [[Video game remake|remake]]s ''Ninja Gaiden Black'' and ''Ninja Gaiden Sigma'' introduced a gameplay variation called Mission Mode. Focused on action rather than character development, this provides combat-based missions set mainly in small areas, where the player's goal is to "destroy all enemies".<ref name="gsngbrev">{{cite web
  | author = [[Greg Kasavin]]
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Black for Xbox Review
  | publisher = [[GameSpot]]
  | date = 2005-09-20
  | url = http://www.gamespot.com/xbox/action/ninjagaidenblack/review.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> In both Story and Mission modes, game scoring is based on the player's speed in clearing encounters, the number of kills achieved, the number of unused magic spells (or ''ninpos'') remaining at the end, and the amount of cash collected. Players can compare their scores on online ranking boards.<ref name="prosigrev">{{cite web
  | author = Will Freeman
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Sigma Review
  | publisher = ''[[Pro-G]]''
  | date = 2007-07-10
  | url = http://www.videogamer.com/ps3/ninja_gaiden_sigma/review.html
  | accessdate = 2008-02-03 }}
</ref>

===Combat system===
Ryu's movements are directed using the console [[gamepad]]. The game's control system, which comprises the left [[analog stick|thumbstick]], two attack buttons, and a block button, was described as "fluid and responsive",<ref>{{cite web
  | author = Alex Kidman
  | title = Ninja Gaiden
  | publisher = [[CNET]] Australia
  | date = 2004-08-02
  | url = http://www.cnet.com.au/games/xbox/0,239029621,219117552,00.htm
  | accessdate = 2007-08-23
  | quote = This gripping feeling is accentuated by the game's controls, which are both fluid and responsive, whether in the pure platform-like sections (think ''[[Prince of Persia: The Sands of Time]]'', especially when Ryu's running along walls or flipping himself out of pits) or the core of the game's challenge, the combat sections. }}
</ref><ref name="ign_inter">{{cite web
  | author = Aaron Boulding
  | title = Ninja Gaiden: The Interview
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2003-06-25
  | url = http://xbox.ign.com/articles/426/426010p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref><ref name="denngb">{{cite web
  | author = Ludwig Kietzmann
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Black
  | publisher = Digital Entertainment News
  | date = 2006-03-23
  | url = http://dignews.com/review.php?story_id=14316
  | accessdate = 2007-08-22 }}
</ref> and ''Ninja Gaiden'' was regarded as having one of the deeper combat engines among [[Xbox]] games at the time, comparing well to the {{nowraplinks}}[[PlayStation 2]]{{nowraplinks end}} action-adventures ''[[God of War (video game)|God of War]]'' and ''[[Devil May Cry (series)|Devil May Cry]]''.<ref name="mech">{{cite web
  | author = Eric Williams
  | title = Combat Canceled: God of War & Action Game Design
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2008-02-15
  | url = http://www.gamasutra.com/php-bin/news_index.php?story=17215
  | accessdate = 2008-02-21 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | author = Tom Orry
  | title = God of War: Chains of Olympus Review
  | publisher = [[Pro-G]]
  | date = 2008-03-28
  | url = http://www.videogamer.com/psp/god_of_war_chains_of_olympus/review.html
  | accessdate = 2008-05-31 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | author = Christian Nutt
  | title = Ninja Gaiden (Xbox)
  | publisher = [[GameSpy]]
  | date = 2004-02-27
  | url = http://xbox.gamespy.com/xbox/ninja-gaiden/499692p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> Eric Williams, the designer of the ''God of War'' combat engine, explained that ''Ninja Gaiden'' prohibits players from stopping or changing attacks in mid-stroke. In contrast, ''God of War'' allows players to do so, and ''Devil May Cry'' grants this freedom to certain attacks. Williams said that, compared to those two games, the combat system in ''Ninja Gaiden'' was harder to master; however, it let players fight their computer controlled foes on equal terms.<ref name="mech" />

[[Image:Ninja Gaiden DS Prep.jpg|thumb|left|In ''Ninja Gaiden'', players can draw in 'essences' to launch Ultimate Techniques that allow Ryu to damage enemies without taking damage himself. Click [[Media:Ninja Gaiden DS UT.gif|here]] to watch an Ultimate Technique in action. ]]
''Ninja Gaiden'' features a large selection of weapons for Ryu to wield, each with advantages and disadvantages that affect the way the player approaches combat. These include one-handed swords, such as the Dragon Sword and Kitetsu, which grant quick attacks and a move called the "Flying Swallow", that allows Ryu to leap and slash through enemies. In addition these light weapons allow Ryu to smash foes into the ground and perform his signature Izuna Drop&mdash;a spinning [[Piledriver (professional wrestling)|piledriver]]. Heavy weapons, such as the Dabilahro and the Unlabored Flawlessness, are slow but cause more damage to opponents. With [[flail]]s and [[Staff (stick)|staves]], the player can string together long sequences of attacks, and to engage distant foes Ryu can throw [[shuriken]] and shoot arrows.<ref name="gsngrev" /><ref>{{cite web
  | author = Hilary Goldstein
  | title = Ninja Gaiden: Blade Love
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2004-02-25
  | url = http://xbox.ign.com/articles/494/494669p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref>

In addition to using standard melee techniques, Ryu can employ 'essences' in combat. These are colored globes of energy that are released on the death of enemies, and absorbed into Ryu's body when he comes into proximity with them. Essences have an important role in general gameplay, acting to heal Ryu, restore his magic, or increase his cash. However, in combat the player can cause Ryu to deliberately draw in essences, which can then be used to unleash powerful attacks known as Ultimate Techniques.<ref name="denngb" /> These techniques deal heavy damage and make Ryu immune to injury for a short time.<ref name="eurong">{{cite web
  | author = Tom Bramwell
  | title = Ninja Gaiden
  | publisher = [[Eurogamer]]
  | date = 2004-03-16
  | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/article.php?article_id=54896
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref>

''Ninja Gaiden'' also provides Ryu with magical spells in the form of ''ninpos''. When activated by the player, these make Ryu cast fireballs, ice storms, or bolts of lightning. Functioning in a similar manner to the bombs or grenades of [[Shoot 'em up|shooter action games]], these spells allow Ryu to inflict heavy damage on enemies while potentially avoiding damage himself.<ref name="ignngrev">{{cite web
  | author = Hilary Goldstein
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Review
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2004-02-27
  | url = http://xbox.ign.com/articles/495/495186p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> However, dissatisfied with their programmed visual effects, the [[game director]] [[Tomonobu Itagaki]] wanted to deter players from using ninpos. He therefore tweaked the game to award bonus points when players cleared stages without employing magic.<ref>{{cite web
  | author = James Mielke
  | title = Previews: Ninja Gaiden 2
  | publisher = [[1UP.com]]
  | date = 2007-11-16
  | url = http://www.1up.com/do/previewPage?cId=3164447
  | accessdate = 2007-11-16 }}
</ref>

For Ryu's defense, the player has two options. First, Ryu can stand still and attempt to block attacks. However, certain enemies can break his guard&mdash;either through particularly strong attacks or by [[grappling]] him. The second option is to make Ryu dodge, by rolling away from the attack in a maneuver called "reverse wind".<ref name="denngb" />
<br style="clear:left;"/>

==Plot and setting==
[[Image:NGB Meeting Alma.jpg|thumb|right|''Ninja Gaiden'' draws on real world architectural styles, such as this [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]] monastery.]]
''Ninja Gaiden'' is set in the game world of another [[Tecmo]] release, ''[[Dead or Alive (series)|Dead or Alive]]'' (''DOA'').<ref name="teamxbox_int">{{cite web
  | author = César A. Berardini
  | title = Ninja Gaiden: Tomonobu Itagaki Interview
  | publisher = [[TeamXbox]]
  | date = 2003-12-05
  | url = http://interviews.teamxbox.com/xbox/701/Ninja-Gaiden-Tomonobu-Itagaki-Interview/p1/
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> Located mainly in [[Japan]] and the fictional Vigoor Empire, the game draws on [[Japanese architecture#Heian period|Heian period]] structures for its Japanese locales&mdash;a [[ninja]] fortress and village set in the mountains. In contrast the Vigoor Empire, with its capital city of Tairon, is a blend of architectural types from around the world.<ref name="eurong" /> [[Europe]]an-style buildings display [[Arabic language|Arabic]] lettering, and the monastery in Tairon exhibits [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]] influences with a vaulted hall, pointed arches, and large stained glass windows. A hidden underground level features statues with the heads of cats, walls covered with carvings, and [[Egyptian hieroglyphs|hieroglyphics]], and [[Team Ninja]] included an [[Mesoamerican pyramids|Aztec pyramid]] and a [[labyrinth]].{{Fact|date=August 2008}} This [[wikt:hodgepodge|hodgepodge]] of styles was the result of Itagaki's deliberate refusal to constrain the game's creative process.<ref name="teamxbox_int" />

===Characters===
{{main|List of Ninja Gaiden characters}}
[[List of Ninja Gaiden characters#Ryu Hayabusa 2|Ryu Hayabusa]], the "super ninja", is the protagonist of ''Ninja Gaiden'',<ref>{{cite web
  | author = James Mielke 
  | title = Itagaki Talks DOA4 Demo on Live
  | publisher = [[1UP.com]]
  | date = 2006-07-24
  | url = http://www.1up.com/do/newsStory?cId=3152406
  | quote = Tomonobu Itagaki: First of all, I have of course included the eternal heroine, Kasumi, as well as everyone's favorite Super Ninja, Ryu Hayabusa.
  | accessdate = 2007-10-08 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | author = GameSpy staff 
  | title = Dead or Alive 4 Guys Week #1 (X360)
  | publisher = [[GameSpy]]
  | date = 2005-10-25
  | url = http://xbox360.gamespy.com/xbox-360/dead-or-alive-4/657005p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-10-08 }}
</ref> and the only player-controllable character in the game. Itagaki believed that creating extra player characters might distract his team from focusing on Ryu's development.<ref name="gmr">{{cite journal
  | author = James Mielke
  | title = Ninja Gaiden
  | journal = [[GMR (magazine)|GMR]]
  | publisher = [[Ziff-Davis]]
  | location = California, United States
  | year = 2003
  | month = July
  | issn = 1544-6816
  | quote = Tomonobu Itagaki: We're not really that interested in making supporting characters playable. Right now, we are simply focusing on making the movements and actions of our "Super Ninja" Ryu Hayabusa the coolest on the planet. }}
</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | author = James Mielke
  | title = Itagaki Hardcore Part 1: The Future of Team Ninja
  | publisher = [[1UP.com]]
  | date = 2005-09-27
  | url = http://www.1up.com/do/feature?cId=3144132
  | accessdate = 2007-10-01 }}
</ref> Ryu has a long history with Tecmo; he was the star of the 1990s ''[[Ninja Gaiden#NES trilogy|Ninja Gaiden]]'' series, and has been part of the ''DOA'' roster since 1996. His roles in these games played a part in his popularity among fans and the game industry.<ref name="history">{{cite web
  | author = Rus McLaughlin
  | title = IGN Presents The History of Ninja Gaiden
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2008-01-28
  | url = http://retro.ign.com/articles/848/848155p1.html
  | accessdate = 2008-01-29 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite video
  | people     = [[ScrewAttack]]
  | date2      = 2007-08-28
  | title      = Top Ten Ninjas
  | url        = http://www.gametrailers.com/player/24269.html
  | format     = swf
  | publisher  = [[GameTrailers]]
  | accessdate = 2008-03-30
  | time       = 05:20 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | author = Jeff "Mr. Nash" Nash
  | title = Weekly Top 10: Best Ninjas
  | publisher = The Armchair Empire
  | date = 2006-03-06
  | url = http://www.armchairempire.com/Features/Weekly-Top-10/best-ninjas.htm
  | accessdate = 2008-03-30 }}
</ref> ''Ninja Gaiden'' provides a backstory to Ryu's appearance and character as seen in the ''Dead or Alive'' series, being set two years before the first ''DOA'' game.<ref name="teamxbox_int" /><ref name="history" />

[[List of Ninja Gaiden characters#Supporting characters 2|Rachel]] is the leading female character, and [[tragic hero]]ine of the game. She and her twin sister, [[List of Ninja Gaiden characters#Leaders of the Fiends|Alma]], are afflicted with a blood curse that turns humans into [[List of Ninja Gaiden characters#Fiends|fiends]].<ref>{{cite video game
  | title = Ninja Gaiden
  | developer = [[Team Ninja]]
  | publisher = [[Tecmo]]
  | date = 2004-03-02
  | platform = [[Xbox]]
  | quote = Rachel: It's hard to believe they were ever humans, isn't it?&nbsp;[...] Anyone with susceptibility to the curse, whether they are a saint or a sinner, can succumb to it and become a Fiend. }}
</ref> Believing that there is no cure for their condition, Rachel seeks to kill Alma to redeem her sister's soul. The relationship between the sisters and the Greater Fiend [[List of Ninja Gaiden characters#Leaders of the Fiends|Doku]], who cursed them, serves as a [[plot device]] to drive the game forward,<ref>{{cite video game
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Sigma
  | developer = [[Team Ninja]]
  | publisher = [[Tecmo]]
  | date = 2007-07-03
  | platform = [[PlayStation 3]]
  | quote = Rachel: I was convinced once that my blood was pure... but then I saw what my pure blood was capable of. I watched as my twin sister was cursed and twisted into a Greater Fiend. Now I know the path I walk is narrow. }}
</ref> with Rachel occasionally needing to be [[damsel in distress|rescued]] by Ryu. Although not a player-controlled character in ''Ninja Gaiden'', in a few sections of the ''Ninja Gaiden Sigma'' remake she is controllable.<ref name="sigpre" />

Two other characters assist the player in the game. [[List of Ninja Gaiden characters#Supporting characters 2|Ayane]], a female ninja and one of the ''DOA'' regular cast members, acts as a guide throughout ''Ninja Gaiden'' by supplying advice and objectives to the player. [[List of Ninja Gaiden characters#Supporting characters 2|Muramasa]], a [[bladesmith]], has shops scattered throughout the game world where players can purchase useful items and upgrades for Ryu's weapons. Muramasa also gives [[quest (gaming)|quests]] and relates [[back-story|back-stories]] and other crucial information; for example, he tells Ryu how he can obtain the item required to upgrade his Dragon Sword to its full potential.

Itagaki found it more interesting to design nonhuman creatures than human enemies,<ref name="giint" /> and as such, most of the enemies Team Ninja created for Ryu are fiends&mdash;humans changed into monsters by their blood curse. Three Greater Fiends lead their lesser brethren against Ryu, playing major roles in the game's plot: Alma, Rachel's sister, whose story forms a significant part of the game; Doku, Ryu's main [[antagonist (literature)|antagonist]], whose raid on Hayabusa village and theft of the Dark Dragon Blade comprise the main plot thread; and [[List of Ninja Gaiden characters#Leaders of the Fiends|Marbus]], who is responsible for the final set of challenges Ryu faces before encountering the Emperor of the fiends.<ref>{{cite video game
  | title = Ninja Gaiden
  | developer = [[Team Ninja]]
  | publisher = [[Tecmo]]
  | date = 2004-03-02
  | platform = [[Xbox]]
  | quote = Ryu: So, the Greater Fiends have a soul, don't they?<br />Rachel: [...] There are only three of them, Doku, my sister and another who guards the Emperor. }}
</ref>

Team Ninja based their [[3D modeling|3D computer models]], from the pistols of the henchman upwards, on real world material. Character models were taken from studies of human anatomy, and the team hired [[Martial arts|martial artists]] in order to digitally capture their movement. Rather than import the [[motion capture]]s directly into the game, however, the animators used them as templates to give a sense of realism to the game characters' exaggerated movements. Players have the option to customize the appearance of player characters, with selectable costumes for Ryu and hairstyles for Rachel.<ref name="sigpre" />

===Story===
Ryu's quest for vengeance spans sixteen chapters, each beginning and ending with a cut scene. At the start of the game, the player takes control of Ryu as he infiltrates the Shadow clan fortress. Ryu is there to visit his uncle, the clan leader [[List of Ninja Gaiden characters#Ninjas|Murai]]. During their chat, Ayane delivers news of a raid on the Hayabusa village. Fighting his way back to his village, Ryu encounters Doku, who has killed the Hayabusa [[miko|shrine maiden]] Kureha and has taken the Dark Dragon Blade. Ryu is cut down by Doku with the stolen Blade, but he is brought back to life as a "soldier of revenge" by a falcon, the spiritual animal of the Hayabusas.<ref>{{cite journal
  | author = Chris Johnston
  | title = Ninja Gaiden
  | journal = [[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]
  | publisher = [[Ziff-Davis]]
  | location = California, United States
  | year = 2004
  | month = June
  | issn = 1058-918X
  | url = http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-21191655_ITM
  | accessdate = 2007-09-05
  | quote = Tomonobu Itagaki: Yes, he died. Do you remember the falcon staring at his dead body? That falcon’s spiritual power resurrected him as a soldier of revenge. }}
</ref>

Seeking vengeance for Kureha's death, Ryu learns from Murai that the raiders were from Vigoor, so he stows away on an [[airship]] bound for the empire.<ref name="gmr" /> Fighting his way through the streets of its capital city, Tairon, Ryu faces several [[boss (video games)|bosses]] including the three Greater Fiends. He defeats Alma in a battle that wrecks the city, but leaves her to Rachel's mercy. However, Rachel cannot bring herself to kill her sister,<ref>{{cite video game
  | title = Ninja Gaiden
  | developer = [[Team Ninja]]
  | publisher = [[Tecmo]]
  | date = 2004-03-02
  | platform = [[Xbox]]
  | quote = Doku: Ah... Rachel. I should kill you now for the pain you've inflicted on Alma, but instead, I shall use you to make her even stronger. It will be your blood, the cursed blood of a twin sister that shall serve to awaken Alma. }}
</ref> and instead is taken by Doku, who prepares to sacrifice her in a ritual to enhance Alma's power. With Alma's help Ryu rescues Rachel and destroys Doku's spirit, but with his dying breath Doku casts the blood curse on Ryu.<ref>{{cite video game
  | title = Ninja Gaiden
  | developer = [[Team Ninja]]
  | publisher = [[Tecmo]]
  | date = 2004-03-02
  | platform = [[Xbox]]
  | quote = Spirit Doku: Receive the curse, become a Fiend. }}
</ref> The only way for Ryu to lift the curse is to kill the emperor, so he storms the palace, defeating Marbus who bars his way to the emperor's personal realm. Two successive boss fights must be completed to destroy the Emperor and reclaim the Dark Dragon Blade&mdash;once this is accomplished his realm starts to destruct. Ryu must then be maneuvered [[Jumping puzzle|up a series of ledges]] to escape, but in the process he loses his grip on the Dark Dragon Blade.

The fallen Blade lands at the feet of a figure, the Dark Disciple, who has been shadowing Ryu throughout the game. Taking the Blade, the Disciple reveals himself to be the clan leader Murai. He admits that the raid on Hayabusa village was part of his plan to restore the Blade's evil power, using souls harvested by Ryu.<ref>{{cite video game
  | title = Ninja Gaiden
  | developer = [[Team Ninja]]
  | publisher = [[Tecmo]]
  | date = 2004-03-02
  | platform = [[Xbox]]
  | quote = Dark Disciple: Gamov, so the Dark Dragon grows in power with each killing. }}
</ref><ref>{{cite video game
  | title = Ninja Gaiden
  | developer = [[Team Ninja]]
  | publisher = [[Tecmo]]
  | date = 2004-03-02
  | platform = [[Xbox]]
  | quote = Gamov: Don't you see? The Dark Dragon is now truly an evil blade. His Excellency the Dark Disciple has been waiting for this very moment! }}
</ref> Drawing on the Blade, Murai transforms himself, setting the stage for the final boss fight. Ryu defeats Murai and shatters the Blade with the True Dragon Sword. Victorious, Ryu turns himself into a falcon and flies to the Hayabusa village. In the game's final scene he places the Dragon Eye, used to enhance his sword, on Kureha's tombstone and disappears into the night. The story of ''Ninja Gaiden'' is continued in the sequels ''[[Ninja Gaiden Dragon Sword]]'' and ''[[Ninja Gaiden II (2008 video game)|Ninja Gaiden II]]''.
<br style="clear:left;"/>

==Development==
In 1999, Team Ninja started work on the "Next-Generation Ninja Gaiden Project".<ref name="history" /> The first stage of development was to create the game on the [[List of Sega arcade system boards#Sega NAOMI|Sega NAOMI]] arcade system board. They then planned to move the project to the [[Dreamcast]] console for further development and release, but this was abandoned when Sega announced the end of Dreamcast product line in 2001.<ref name="edge" /> At this point, Tecmo decided to release ''Ninja Gaiden'' as a launch title for the [[Sony Computer Entertainment|Sony]] {{nowraplinks}}[[PlayStation 2]]{{nowraplinks end}} in the United States.<ref>{{cite news
  | author = Sam Kennedy
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Goes PlayStation 2
  | publisher = [[GameSpot]]
  | date = 1999-06-03
  | url = http://www.gamespot.com/news/2450994.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> Itagaki, however, had other plans; the Team Ninja Leader was impressed with the [[software development kit]]s for the Xbox and pushed for his team to develop for the [[Microsoft]] console.<ref name="history" /> The company kept silent on this change in direction, and surprised both the games industry and fans when they announced at [[E3 Media and Business Summit|E3 2002]] that ''Ninja Gaiden'' was exclusive to the Xbox.<ref name="armemp">{{cite web
  | author = Aaron "Omni" Simmer
  | title = Xbox Previews: Ninja Gaiden
  | publisher = The Armchair Empire
  | date = 2003-04-05
  | url = http://www.armchairempire.com/Previews/Xbox/ninja-gaiden.htm
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> Most fans who voted on Tecmo's poll wanted the game on the [[Nintendo]] [[GameCube]].<ref>{{cite news
  | author = IGN staff
  | title = Ninja Gaiden on PS2?
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2001-06-29
  | url = http://ps2.ign.com/articles/096/096210p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref>

''Ninja Gaiden'' was Team Ninja's first action title. Its initial concept had nothing in common with the original ''[[Ninja Gaiden#NES trilogy|Ninja Gaiden]]'' series, released on the [[Nintendo Entertainment System]].<ref name="wint">{{cite journal
  | author = Xbox Nation staff
  | title = Paradise Lost
  | journal = Xbox Nation
  | publisher = [[Ziff Davis]]
  | location = California, United States
  | issn = 1538-9723
  | year = 2002
  | month = Winter
  | url = http://bellsouthpwp.net/r/a/racerg/itagaki-xbn-winter2002.html
  | accessdate = 2007-09-23 }}
</ref> However, for retail reasons Tecmo wanted to retain a link with the previous games, which had many adherents in the [[Western world|West]],<ref name="history" /> so Itagaki was asked to rethink his ideas to target the foreign market.<ref name="wint" /><ref name="edge" /> Analysing the earlier games, he concluded that their violence appealed to players, and included gory content, such as beheadings, in the Xbox game to retain that spirit.<ref name="edge" /> He also aimed to make his new game hard but alluring;<ref name="teamxbox_int" /> it would challenge players on their reflexes rather than on their memories of layouts and timings.<ref name="ign_inter" /> His team made a point of designing smoothly-flowing gameplay with high-quality animations that reacted quickly to the player's input.<ref name="teamxbox_int" /> Itagaki paid homage to the earlier ''Ninja Gaiden'' series by including updated versions of foes and special attacks.<ref name="gsngrev" /><ref name="ignngrev" />

In 2004 Tecmo released a [[game demo|demo disc]] of ''Ninja Gaiden'' in Japan, bundled with the [[February 26]] issue of ''[[Famitsu|Famitsu Xbox]]'' magazine.<ref>{{cite news
  | author = IGN staff
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Demo Disc
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2004-01-20
  | url = http://xbox.ign.com/articles/473/473498p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> The demo let players try the first chapter of the game on two difficulty settings with a few fully upgraded weapons and ninpos.<ref>{{cite web
  | author = Anoop Gantayat
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Demo Busted
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2004-02-13
  | url = http://xbox.ign.com/articles/492/492400p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> On [[March 2]] [[2004]], a year later than originally planned, Tecmo released ''Ninja Gaiden''.<ref name="armemp" /><ref>{{cite press release
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Release Date Locked Down
  | publisher = [[Tecmo]]
  | date = 2004-02-24
  | url = http://www.armchairempire.com/videogame-news/Xbox/Febraury-2004/ninja-gaiden-release-date.htm
  | accessdate = 2007-08-23 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite news
  | author = IGN staff
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Still On Track
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2003-09-19
  | url = http://xbox.ign.com/articles/450/450798p1.html
  | accessdate = 2008-04-21 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite news
  | author = IGN staff
  | title = More Ninja Gaiden
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2003-12-01
  | url = http://xbox.ign.com/articles/442/442537p1.html
  | accessdate = 2008-04-21 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite news
  | author = IGN staff
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Delay
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2004-01-29
  | url = http://xbox.ign.com/articles/481/481455p1.html
  | accessdate = 2008-04-21 }}
</ref>

===Post-release===
Team Ninja kept working on the ''Ninja Gaiden'' project after its release, with the aim of pushing the action genre and their first such title as far as they could.<ref name="giint">{{cite web
  | author = Billy Berghammer
  | title = An Interivew With Tomonobu Itagaki
  | publisher = ''[[Game Informer]]''
  | date = 2004-07-27
  | url = http://www.gameinformer.com/News/Story/200407/N04.0727.1752.42649.htm
  | accessdate = 2008-01-05 }}
</ref> To this end, they released downloadable expansions, known as "Hurricane Packs", free of charge. Itagaki said that since the packs were born out of his team's interest, they did not care to charge players for their efforts.<ref>{{cite web
  | author = Hilary Goldstein
  | title = Ninja Gaiden: Hurricane Pack Vol. 1 Q&A
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2004-07-16
  | url = http://xbox.ign.com/articles/531/531106p1.html
  | accessdate = 2008-02-10 }}
</ref>

The two Packs were available over [[Xbox Live]] in the third quarter of 2004. ''Hurricane Pack&nbsp;1'' was a revamped version of Story Mode; Team Ninja tweaked the encounters and [[Game artificial intelligence|artificial intelligence]] (AI) of Ryu's foes to increase the difficulty of the game. The pack introduced additional foes such as humanoid cats, giants wearing ''[[Triceratops]]'' skulls, and [[cyborg]]s, and Team Ninja made a key change to the camera system by which the on-screen action is displayed; players could now control the camera and change its viewing angle.<ref name="hurhands1">{{cite web
  | author = Hilary Goldstein
  | title = Ninja Gaiden: Hurricane Pack Vol. 1 Hands-On
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2004-07-21
  | url = http://xbox.ign.com/articles/532/532309p1.html
  | accessdate = 2008-02-10 }}
</ref> Another feature of the pack was to enhance the combat engine; the new "Intercept" skill let players [[wikt:counter|counter]] any enemy attack with the proper timing.<ref>{{cite web
  | author = Hilary Goldstein
  | title = Ninja Gaiden: Intercept
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2004-07-28
  | url = http://xbox.ign.com/articles/534/534280p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref>

''Hurricane Pack&nbsp;2'' kept the enhancements of the first, but took place in an alternative world comprising only two regions, where players have to fight through several encounters to rescue Rachel from two new bosses ([[List of Ninja Gaiden characters#Fiends|Nicchae]] and [[List of Ninja Gaiden characters#Fiends|Ishtaros]]). This expansion introduced the Lunar staff, and fiends who wield giant swords and cast fireballs.<ref>{{cite web
  | author = Hilary Goldstein
  | title = Ninja Gaiden: Hurricane Pack Vol. 2 Hands-On
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2004-09-22
  | url = http://xbox.ign.com/articles/550/550203p1.html
  | accessdate = 2008-02-10 }}
</ref>

Team Ninja later compiled both expansion packs, and added new features, to create ''Ninja Gaiden Black'' (''Black''). This game, which Itagaki viewed as the final version of ''Ninja Gaiden'',<ref name="devint">{{cite web
  | author = Cory J. Herndon
  | title = Dev Interview: Tecmo w/Itagaki-san
  | publisher = Xbox.com
  | date = 2005-05-23
  | url = http://www.xbox.com/en-US/games/d/deadoralive4/20050523-tecmo.htm
  | accessdate = 2007-09-23 }}
</ref> went on sale on [[September 20]], [[2005]].<ref>{{cite press release
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Black Ships to Retailers
  | publisher = [[Tecmo]]
  | date = 2005-09-21
  | url = http://64.78.9.175/press.asp?id=20
  | accessdate = 2007-08-23 }}
</ref> A few years later, Team Ninja upgraded the graphics of the game and [[porting|ported]] it to the {{nowraplinks}}[[PlayStation 3]]{{nowraplinks end}} (PS3). This version was released as ''Ninja Gaiden Sigma'' (''Sigma'') on [[June 14]], [[2007]]. ''Black'' became an [[Xbox Live Marketplace#Xbox Originals|Xbox Original]] game on [[February 11]], [[2008]].<ref>{{cite news
  | author = Hilary Goldstein
  | title = New Xbox Originals on the Horizon
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2008-02-05
  | url = http://xbox360.ign.com/articles/849/849621p1.html
  | accessdate = 2008-02-21 }}
</ref>

===Regional censorship===
<div style="font-size: 90%;float:right;border-left:1em solid white">
{| class="wikitable"
|+ Human beheadings featured
! &nbsp; !! [[NTSC-J]] !! [[NTSC#US_Video_Game_Region|NTSC-US]] !! [[PAL region|PAL]]
|-
! ''Ninja Gaiden''
|align="center" bgcolor="#A0F898" | Yes
|align="center" bgcolor="#A0F898" | Yes
|align="center" bgcolor="#FF90A8" | No
|-
! ''Ninja Gaiden Black''
|align="center" bgcolor="#A0F898" | Yes
|align="center" bgcolor="#A0F898" | Yes
|align="center" bgcolor="#A0F898" | Yes
|-
! ''Ninja Gaiden Sigma''
|align="center" bgcolor="#FF90A8" | No
|align="center" bgcolor="#A0F898" | Yes
|align="center" bgcolor="#FF90A8" | No
|}
</div>
As released, ''Ninja Gaiden'' contained bloody acts of violence, [[decapitation|beheadings]], and grotesque monsters. The North American games rating body, the [[Entertainment Software Rating Board]] (ESRB), rated it as a "Mature" game, which prohibits sale to anyone under the age of 17.<ref>{{cite news
  | author = Tor Thorsen
  | title = Ninja Gaiden: Not for kids!
  | publisher = [[GameSpot]]
  | date = 2004-01-20
  | url = http://www.gamespot.com/xbox/action/ninjagaiden/news.html?sid=6086698
  | accessdate = 2008-02-11 }}
</ref> However, the depiction of beheadings attracts stricter ratings in other parts of the world.<ref>{{cite news
  | author = Alex Navarro
  | title = Ninja Gaiden could get Euro makeover
  | publisher = [[GameSpot]]
  | date = 2004-03-11
  | url = http://www.gamespot.com/news/6091272.html
  | accessdate = 2008-05-08 }}
</ref> In [[Germany]], the [[Unterhaltungssoftware Selbstkontrolle]] (USK) deemed these excessive, and refused to rate the game at all. Since this had the potential to place ''Ninja Gaiden'' in Germany's "[[Bundesprüfstelle für jugendgefährdende Medien#The List of Media Harmful to Young People|List of Media Harmful to Young People]]", which would have meant that shops could neither advertise the game nor sell it unless by request to customers of 18 years or older,<ref name="censor">{{cite web
  | author = Dan Chiappini 
  | title = Censory Overload&mdash;Australia vs. World
  | publisher = [[GameSpot|GameSpot AU]]
  | date = 2008-04-10
  | url = http://www.gamespot.com/features/6188493/p-3.html
  | accessdate = 2008-04-26 }}
</ref> Tecmo censored the European [[PAL region|PAL]] version to obtain a USK rating.<ref>{{cite news
  | author = 1UP staff
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Censored In Europe
  | publisher = [[1UP.com]]
  | year = 2004
  | url = http://www.1up.com/do/newsStory?cId=3125273
  | accessdate = 2008-05-04 }}
</ref> A year later, Tecmo managed to obtain a USK 18+ rating for the uncensored release of ''Ninja Gaiden Black'', but ''Ninja Gaiden Sigma'' was censored for release under the same rating.

Due to the [[Australia]]n [[Office of Film and Literature Classification (Australia)|Office of Film and Literature Classification]]'s (OFLC) strict standards,<ref name="censor" /> ''Ninja Gaiden Black'' was unlikely to qualify for even its highest rating, MA15+. The OFLC will usually refuse to rate such games, and it is illegal to sell or advertise these games in Australia.<ref>{{cite web
  | author = Dan Chiappini 
  | title = Censory Overload&mdash;History of AU Classification
  | publisher = [[GameSpot|GameSpot AU]]
  | date = 2008-04-01
  | url = http://www.gamespot.com/features/6188493/index.html
  | accessdate = 2008-04-26 }} Sales of these games are legally enforced, and particularly gory games, especially those with beheadings, tend not to qualify for this rating. 
</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | author = Classification Policy Branch
  | title = Classification categories and markings
  | publisher = Australian Government Attoney-General's Department
  | date = 2007-06-13
  | url = http://www.ag.gov.au/www/agd/agd.nsf/Page/Classificationpolicy_Classificationcategoriesandmarkings
  | accessdate = 2008-06-20 }}
</ref> Thus, unlike ''Sigma'', Tecmo did not submit ''Ninja Gaiden Black'' to the OFLC, and it never saw an Australian release.<ref>{{cite web
  | author = Jeremy Jastrzab
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Sigma Review
  | publisher = [[PALGN|PAL Gaming Network]]
  | date = 2007-08-06
  | url = http://palgn.co.uk/article.php?id=8346
  | accessdate = 2007-08-23 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite news
  | author = Chienne
  | title =  OFLC vs Xbox Originals = Casualty: Ninja Gaiden: Black
  | publisher = [[Internode Systems|Internode Games Network]]
  | date = 2008-02-13
  | url = http://games.internode.on.net/content.php?mode=news&id=2604
  | accessdate = 2008-03-21 }}
</ref>

Japan's [[Computer Entertainment Rating Organization]] (CERO) rated ''Ninja Gaiden'' and ''Black'', on their release, as 18+ games.<ref name="cesa">{{cite news
  | author = CESA staff
  | title = 旧18才以上対象ソフト再審査結果一覧（2006．05．30現在）
  | publisher = [[Computer Entertainment Supplier's Association]]
  | date = 2006-05-30
  | url = http://www.cesa.or.jp/news/2006/060530.pdf
  | format = PDF
  | language = {{Ja icon}}
  | accessdate = 2008-03-21 }}
</ref> At the time, CERO ratings acted as guidelines for consumers. However, on [[March 1]], [[2006]], the Japanese rating system changed. A scale from A to D was introduced, with an additional Z rating for games with large amounts of gore and sexual content. The Z rating is legally enforced, it being illegal to sell such games to anyone under the age of 18.<ref>{{cite web
  | author = David Jenkins
  | title = Japan To Introduce Revised CERO Ratings System
  | publisher = [[Gamasutra]]
  | date = 2006-02-17
  | url = http://www.gamasutra.com/php-bin/news_index.php?story=8213
  | accessdate = 2008-02-10 }}
</ref> As a result, Tecmo removed the human beheadings in ''Sigma'' to obtain a D rating for the [[East Asia]]n market. However, CERO reclassified the two previous games as D, despite them also depicting human beheadings.<ref name="cesa" />
{{-}}

==Online competition==
[[Image:MNT Game On.jpg|thumb|left|The finalists played on walkways above the crowd while commentators talked about their actions on the big screen.]]
The Master Ninja Tournaments were a series of three online contests held by Microsoft and Tecmo in 2004. They took place over Xbox Live, and were open to participants in Europe, Japan, and North America. Winner selection was based on the scores achieved through playing ''Ninja Gaiden'' or its ''Hurricane Packs''; players had 14 to 24&nbsp;days to complete the required games and submit their scores to an online scoreboard.<ref>{{cite news
  | author = Stephen Coleman
  | title = Master Ninja Tournament Registration Extended
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2004-08-03
  | url = http://games.ign.com/articles/535/535413p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite news
  | author = César Berardini
  | title = Tecmo Announces Master Ninja Tournament Round 2
  | publisher = [[TeamXbox]]
  | date = 2004-07-12
  | url = http://news.teamxbox.com/xbox/6261/Tecmo-Announces-Master-Ninja-Tournament-Round-2/
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | url = http://plusd.itmedia.co.jp/games/gsnews/0408/03/news09.html
  | title = 「Ninja Gaiden」世界大会の参加登録延長に
  | accessdate = 2008-03-25
  | author = Softbank Games staff
  | publisher = Softbank Games
  | date = 2004-08-03
  | language = {{Ja icon}} }}
</ref>

The first two tournaments formed regional qualification stages for a live ''Ninja Gaiden'' Master Tournament World Championship, held on [[September 25]] at the [[Tokyo Game Show|Tokyo Game Show 2004]]. Competition for places was intense, with both tournaments breaking records for online participation in Xbox Live events.<ref name="lotsninja">{{cite press release
  | title = Lots O' Ninjas
  | publisher = Digital Entertainment News
  | date = 2004-05-28
  | url = http://www.dignews.com/news.php?story_id=3686
  | accessdate = 2008-02-03 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite press release
  | title = Master Ninja Tournament Breaks Records Again with Highest Registration Numbers
  | publisher = [[GameSpot]]
  | date = 2004-09-03
  | url = http://www.gamespot.com/xbox/action/ninjagaiden/news.html?sid=6106689&mode=press
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref>  Six of the highest scoring players from Europe and North America won [[bokken]]s bearing Itagaki's signature,<ref name="lotsninja">{{cite press release
  | title = Lots O' Ninjas
  | publisher = Digital Entertainment News
  | date = 2004-05-28
  | url = http://www.dignews.com/news.php?story_id=3686
  | accessdate = 2008-02-03 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite news
  | author = César Berardini
  | title = Master Ninja Tournament for Europe Announced
  | publisher = [[TeamXbox]]
  | date = 2004-07-26
  | url = http://news.teamxbox.com/xbox/6375/Master-Ninja-Tournament-for-Europe-Announced/
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> and five regional winners were selected to proceed to the final. Here, the finalists simultaneously played a custom game drawn from ''Hurricane Pack&nbsp;2'' while commentators called out the action. They had 15&nbsp;minutes to complete the game and post the highest score; the winner emerged only in the last 20&nbsp;seconds, when Yasunori Otsuka cleared the game and outscored his rivals. At the award ceremony, the finalists received their prize plaques from Itagaki.<ref>{{cite web
  | url = http://watch.impress.co.jp/game%2Fdocs/20040925/xbox3.htm
  | title = 世界一のNinja使いがここに決定! 「Master Ninja Tournament 世界決勝戦」がマイクロソフトブースで開催
  | accessdate = 2008-03-25
  | author = 平澤寿康
  | publisher = Game Watch
  | date = 2004-09-25
  | language = {{Ja icon}} }}
</ref><ref>{{cite news
  | author = Chris Carle
  | title = TGS 2004: Ninja Gaiden Master Tournament World Championship
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2004-09-25
  | url = http://xbox.ign.com/articles/551/551186p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref>

The tournaments were not without controversy. Players complained about Microsoft's tardiness in posting the official rules for the first playoff, and it was believed that the top posted score was not achievable by fair means.<ref>{{cite journal
  | author = Xbox Nation staff
  | title = Ninja Nation
  | journal = Xbox Nation
  | pages = p. 28
  | publisher = [[Ziff Davis]]
  | location = California, United States
  | issn = 1538-9723
  | year = 2004
  | month = August
  | url = http://www.xbox-hq.com/html/modules.php?name=News&file=print&sid=1080
  | accessdate = 2007-09-05 }}
</ref> Officials, however, stated that the score was possible, and allowed the results to stand.<ref>{{cite news
  | author = Hilary Goldstein
  | title = Master Ninja Tournament Heats Up
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2004-05-26
  | url = http://xbox.ign.com/articles/519/519150p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> In the second playoff, Microsoft initially named the runner up as the North American finalist after disqualifying the winner,<ref>{{cite news
  | author = César Berardini
  | title = Master Ninja Tournament Finals Details
  | publisher = [[TeamXbox]]
  | date = 2004-09-15
  | url = http://news.teamxbox.com/xbox/6768/Master-Ninja-Tournament-Finals-Details/
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> but eventually had to send the second runner up to Tokyo when the first was unable to produce a passport in time.<ref>{{cite web
  | url = http://plusd.itmedia.co.jp/games/tgs/2004/news/040925/07/index.html
  | title = Master Ninja Tournament 世界決勝戦 勝者は!?
  | accessdate = 2008-03-25
  | author = Softbank Games staff
  | publisher = Softbank Games
  | date = 2004-09-25
  | language = {{Ja icon}} }}
</ref>

Master Ninja Tournament 3 started on [[September 27]] and lasted 26&nbsp;days. Rankings were decided by scores obtained while playing ''Hurricane Pack&nbsp;2'', and the prizes were Tecmo apparel and Team Ninja games.<ref>{{cite press release
  | title = Tecmo Announces Third and Final Master Ninja Tournament, Hurricane Pack: Volume II
  | publisher = [[GameSpot]]
  | date = 2004-09-24
  | url = http://www.gamespot.com/xbox/action/ninjagaiden/news.html?sid=6108698&mode=press
  | accessdate = 2008-01-27 }}
</ref> This marked the end of official tournaments for ''Ninja Gaiden'', although Microsoft have retained the ranking boards for players to upload their scores.
<br style="clear:both;"/>

==Remakes and merchandise==
Tecmo published two remakes of ''Ninja Gaiden'': ''Ninja Gaiden Black'' and ''Ninja Gaiden Sigma''. Essentially the same game as the original, they tell the same story of Ryu and the Dark Dragon Blade, but include additional content and updated game mechanics. Itagaki deemed ''Black'' to be the final version of ''Ninja Gaiden'',<ref name="devint" /> but with the release of the PlayStation 3, Tecmo ported the game to this platform as ''Sigma''.

===''Ninja Gaiden Black''===
Tecmo announced at E3 2005 that Team Ninja was working on ''Ninja Gaiden Black'',<ref>{{cite news
  | author = Douglass C. Perry
  | title = E3 2005: Ninja Gaiden Black is Beautiful
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2005-05-20
  | url = http://xbox.ign.com/articles/618/618262p1.html
  | accessdate = 2008-05-11 }}
</ref> and later exhibited a working version of the game at the 2005 Tokyo Game Show.<ref>{{cite news
  | author = Famitsu staff
  | title = 【ブース】『DOA4』の美麗映像に驚け！ テクモブースは例年以上の大混雑ぶり!!
  | publisher = ''[[Famitsu]]''
  | date = 2005-09-17
  | url = http://www.famitsu.com/game/event/2005/09/14/264,1126670828,43352,0,0.html
  | language = {{Ja icon}}
  | accessdate = 2008-05-04 }}
</ref> ''Black'' is a reworked compilation of the original ''Ninja Gaiden'' and the two ''Hurricane Packs''.<ref name="devint" /> The game features new foes, such as exploding bats and [[doppelgänger]] fiends who can imitate Ryu.<ref name="ngb1uprev">{{cite web
  | author = 1UP.com staff
  | title = Reviews: Ninja Gaiden Black
  | publisher = [[1UP.com]]
  | date = 2005-09-16
  | url = http://www.1up.com/do/reviewPage?cId=3143860
  | accessdate = 2008-03-21 }}
</ref> It contains more costumes than the original, and swaps ''Ninja Gaiden's'' [[Unlockable games|unlockable NES games]] for an [[Ninja Gaiden (arcade)|arcade version]].<ref name="ngbpre">{{cite web
  | author = Rob Semsey
  | title = Ninja Gaiden: Black Hands-On
  | publisher = [[TeamXbox]]
  | date = 2005-08-10
  | url = http://previews.teamxbox.com/xbox/1143/Ninja-Gaiden-BLACK/p1/
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref>

One key feature of the remake is its two new difficulty settings&mdash;the easy 'Ninja Dog', and the very hard 'Master Ninja'.<ref name="denngb" /> Itagaki added Ninja Dog after receiving complaints of ''Ninja Gaiden'' being too hard in its default incarnation,<ref>{{cite news
  | author = James Mielke
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Black from 1UP.com
  | publisher = [[1UP.com]]
  | date = 2005-05-13
  | url = http://www.1up.com/do/feature?pager.offset=0&cId=3140456
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> although he believed that, with persistence, any player was capable of completing the game.<ref>{{cite web
  | author = 1UP.com staff
  | title = Previews: Ninja Gaiden
  | publisher = [[1UP.com]]
  | date = 2004-09-05
  | url = http://www.1up.com/do/previewPage?cId=3061511
  | accessdate = 2007-09-23 }}
</ref> Hence he ensured that those players selecting Ninja Dog would be subjected to gentle mockery by the game&mdash;players on this difficulty setting receive pink ribbons as accessories, and Ayane treats Ryu as an inferior. In compensation, Itagaki made the other difficulty settings harder than in ''Ninja Gaiden''. Ryu's adversaries were strengthened and made more aggressive, and some of his offensive moves, such as the Flying Swallow, were toned down.<ref name="denngb" />

Another feature of ''Black'' is its Mission Mode, which comprises 50&nbsp;combat missions, one of which is adapted from the custom game designed for the Ninja Gaiden Master Tournament World Championship final. The last five missions are based on those in ''Hurricane Pack&nbsp;2'', but with the ''Black'' game engine, and form a linked series known as "Eternal Legend".<ref name="ngbpre" />

===''Ninja Gaiden Sigma''===
In 2006, Tecmo and Sony announced the development of ''Ninja Gaiden Sigma'' for the PS3.<ref>{{cite news
  | author = Andy Robinson
  | title = Ninja Gaiden pulls a flying kick on PS3
  | publisher = ''[[Computer and Video Games]]''
  | date = 2006-09-20
  | url = http://www.computerandvideogames.com/article.php?id=146205
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite news
  | author = Tim Surette
  | coauthors = Brendan Sinclair
  | title = TGS 06: Gaiden, Shirokishi lead new PS3 game charge
  | publisher = [[GameSpot]]
  | date = 2006-09-21
  | url = http://www.gamespot.com/events/tgs2006/story.html?sid=6158162&pid=935677
  | accessdate = 2008-05-04 }}
</ref> [[Eidos Interactive|Eidos]] obtained the European publishing rights for this game.<ref>{{cite news
  | author = Andy Robinson
  | title = Eidos picks up Ninja Gaiden Sigma
  | publisher = ''[[Computer and Video Games]]''
  | date = 2007-04-18
  | url = http://www.computerandvideogames.com/article.php?id=162227
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> Itagaki had no direct role in ''Sigma'', and judged it a flawed game,<ref>{{cite web
  | author = Jon Wilcox
  | title = Itagaki: Ninja Gaiden 2 Is My Final Instalment News
  | publisher = Total Video Games
  | date = 2008-05-13
  | url = http://www.totalvideogames.com/news/Itagaki_Ninja_Gaiden_2_Is_My_Final_Instalment_13219_7010_0.htm
  | accessdate = 2008-05-14 }}
</ref> although he acknowledged that ''Sigma'' gave PlayStation owners a taste of ''Ninja Gaiden''.<ref>{{cite news
  | author = Anoop Gantayat
  | title = No Sigma For 360
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2007-06-01
  | url = http://xbox360.ign.com/articles/793/793679p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref>

The [[Cell (microprocessor)|Cell processor]] of the PS3 gave Team Ninja the opportunity to overhaul the game graphics to use larger and more detailed [[Texture mapping|textures]].<ref name="sigpre" /> Changes were made to the game world, with a few new areas and several additional [[Saved game|save points]] and shops,<ref name="gssigrev" /> and alterations to the game engine let players shoot arrows in mid-air, fight on water surfaces, and play as Rachel in some chapters and missions.<ref name="sigpre" /><ref name="gssigpre">{{cite web
  | author = Gabe Graziani
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Sigma Preview
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2007-05-25
  | url = http://ps3.gamespy.com/playstation-3/ninja-gaiden-sigma/792132p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-09-06 }}
</ref> Team Ninja added more enemies such as bikers, fish-men, and a new boss, Gamov, and Ryu's weapon choices are extended with a pair of [[katana]]s called the Dragon's Claw and Tiger's Fang.<ref name="sigpre" /><ref name="gssigrev">{{cite web
  | author = Kevin VanOrd
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Sigma for PlayStation 3 Review
  | publisher = [[GameSpot]]
  | date = 2007-07-02
  | url = http://www.gamespot.com/ps3/action/ninjagaidensigma/review.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> By shaking the [[PlayStation 3 accessories#Sixaxis|Sixaxis]] controller, players are able to increase the power of their ninpos.<ref>{{cite web
  | author = Rob Fahey
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Sigma
  | publisher = [[Eurogamer]]
  | date = 2007-06-16
  | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/article.php?article_id=77792
  | accessdate = 2008-01-27 }}
</ref> 

Although marketed as the "more complete" version of ''Ninja Gaiden'',<ref>{{cite news
  | author = Walt Wyman
  | title = TGS 06: PS3 Ninja Gaiden Detailed
  | publisher = [[GameSpot]]
  | date = 2007-09-22
  | url = http://www.gamespot.com/news/6158343.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref><ref>
{{cite news
  | author = Anoop Gantayat
  | title = Confirmed: Ninja Gaiden on PS3
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2006-09-20
  | url = http://ps3.ign.com/articles/733/733714p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite news
  | author = Rob Burman
  | title = Eidos Unleashing Ninjas in Europe
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2007-04-20
  | url = http://ps3.ign.com/articles/782/782234p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> ''Sigma'' omits several features found in the Xbox games. It does not have the opening movie or the unlockable games, and has fewer costumes than are available in ''Black''.<ref name="sigpre" /><ref name="gssigpre" /><ref name="ignau">{{cite web 
  | author = Patrick Kolan
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Sigma AU Review
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2007-07-04
  | url = http://ps3.ign.com/articles/801/801548p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> In Japan, Tecmo engaged a local-based singer, [[Leah Dizon]], to promote ''Sigma''. She appeared in a commercial and sang its theme,<ref>{{cite video
  | year = 2007
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Sigma Japan TV Commercial
  | url = http://www.gametrailers.com/player/usermovies/69850.html
  | format = flv
  | medium = Television commercial
  | publisher = [[Tecmo]]
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> and signed posters that Tecmo gave away at the game's launch.<ref>{{cite news
  | author = Famitsu staff
  | title = リア･ディゾンのサイン入りポスターがもらえる！　『NINJA GAIDEN Σ』発売記念イベントが開催決定
  | publisher = ''[[Famitsu]]''
  | date = 2007-06-11
  | url = http://www.famitsu.com/game/news/2007/06/11/103,1181556863,73212,0,0.html
  | language = {{Ja icon}}
  | accessdate = 2008-05-03 }}
</ref> In North America, [[GameStop]] sold [[special edition]]s of ''Sigma'' in their stores.<ref>{{cite press release
  | title = Tecmo Announces the Launch of Ninja Gaiden Sigma
  | publisher = [[Tecmo]]
  | date = 2007-07-02
  | url = http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0EIN/is_2007_July_2/ai_n19330371
  | accessdate = 2008-05-03 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite news
  | author = Rob Purchese
  | title = Sigma Special Edition iffy for Europe
  | publisher = [[Eurogamer]]
  | date = 2007-04-24
  | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/article.php?article_id=75667
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref><ref name="cejp">{{cite news
  | author = Ten-Four
  | title =  海外レビューハイスコア『Ninja Gaiden Sigma』
  | publisher = Game Spark
  | date = 2007-07-05
  | url = http://www.gamespark.jp/modules/news/index.php?p=2886
  | accessdate = 2008-03-21
  | language = {{Ja icon}} }}
</ref> These editions have an exclusive "behind-the-scenes" [[DVD]], and contain a code that unlocks extra missions. However, the code proved to be usable on normal copies of the game.<ref name="cejp" /><ref>{{cite book
  | title = Codes & Cheats
  | origdate = 2007-11-15
  | edition = Winter 2008
  | publisher = [[Prima Games]]
  | location = California, US
  | isbn = 0-761-55668-0 }}
</ref>

In 2007, Tecmo released a demo and a new game mode, Survival Mode, for ''Sigma'' over the [[PlayStation Network]].<ref>{{cite news
  | author = Anoop Gantayat
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Sigma Downloadable Content Announced
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2007-08-03
  | url = http://ps3.ign.com/articles/810/810350p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> The demo limits players to the first chapter of the game, but lets them play as Rachel in a separate mission.<ref>{{cite web
  | author = Richard Leadbetter
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Sigma
  | publisher = [[Eurogamer]]
  | date = 2007-05-02
  | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/article.php?article_id=75934
  | accessdate = 2008-04-21 }}
</ref> Survival Mode comprises missions in which players keep fighting until they have either killed all their opponents, or their character has been defeated.<ref>{{cite web
  | author = Chris Roper
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Sigma Expansion Pack Hands-on
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2007-09-06
  | url = http://ps3.ign.com/articles/818/818522p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-09-06 }}
</ref>

===Merchandise===
Tecmo has built up a line of merchandise around the ''Ninja Gaiden'' name. Its online shop carries apparel and accessories such as caps, wristbands, T-shirts, key holders, and mugs. Most of the merchandise is based on that associated with the various ''Ninja Gaiden'' game launches or given as prizes in the Master Ninja Tournaments.<ref>{{cite news
  | author = Justin Calvert
  | title = Tecmo releases Ninja Gaiden merchandise
  | publisher = [[GameSpot]]
  | date = 2003-12-19
  | url = http://www.gamespot.com/news/6085935.html
  | accessdate = 2008-05-03 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite press release
  | title = Tecmo Announces Free Retro T-Shirt As Ninja Gaiden Black Pre-Order Incentive
  | publisher = [[Tecmo]]
  | date = 2005-09-01
  | url = http://64.78.9.175/press.asp?id=18
  | accessdate = 2007-08-23 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | author = Jack DeVries
  | title = Ottsel's Blog&mdash;In-game reservation gifts: Completely worthless
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2007-07-05
  | url = http://blogs.ign.com/Ottsel/2007/07/05/59292/
  | accessdate = 2008-05-03 }}
</ref> Tecmo also published the original soundtrack of the game under their record label, Wake Up, on [[March 20]], [[2004]]. Kotobukiya, a figurine maker, includes [[1:6 scale modeling|1/6th scale]] [[Model figure|plastic figurines]] of ''Ninja Gaiden'' characters in their range of products. As of 2007, they have produced figures of Ryu, Ayane, Kureha, and Rachel.<ref>{{cite web
  | author = Kotobukiya USA staff
  | title = Ninja Gaiden ARTFX Statues
  | publisher = Kotobukiya USA
  | date = n.d.
  | url = http://www.kotous.com/video-games/ninja-gaiden.php
  | accessdate = 2007-08-27 }}
</ref>

