|-
|<center>''Ninja Gaiden''<br>''Black''
|colspan=3|<center>GameSpot's Best Xbox game 2005<ref>{{cite web |author=GameSpot staff |title=GameSpot's Best of 2005&mdash;Platform Awards |publisher=[[GameSpot]] |date=2006-01-23 |url=http://www.gamespot.com/pages/features/bestof2005/index.php?day=5&page=6 |accessdate=2007-09-05}}</ref><br>IGN's Best Xbox Action game 2005<ref>{{cite web |author=IGN staff |title=IGN Xbox Best of 2005 Awards |publisher=[[IGN]] |date=2005-01-16 |url=http://bestof.ign.com/2005/xbox/1.html |accessdate=2007-09-05}}</ref><br>[[TeamXbox]]'s Best Xbox Action Game 2005<ref>{{cite web |author=TeamXbox staff |title=TeamXbox.com Game of the Year Awards 2005 |publisher=[[TeamXbox]] |date=2005-12-22 |url=http://features.teamxbox.com/xbox/1421/TeamXboxcom-Game-of-the-Year-Awards-2005/p1/ |accessdate=2007-09-05}}</ref>
|-
|<center>''Ninja Gaiden''<br>''Sigma''
|colspan=3|<center>IGN's Game of the Month<ref>{{cite web |author=IGN PlayStation Team |title=Game of the Month: July 2007 |publisher=[[IGN]] |date=2007-07-31 |url=http://ps3.ign.com/articles/809/809607p1.html |accessdate=2007-09-05}}</ref>
|}{{*}} score out of 5
</div>
''Ninja Gaiden'' was released to general critical acclaim. [[GameSpot]] called it "one of the best most challenging action adventure games ever made",<ref name="gsngrev"/> and [[IGN]] said that it "sets a new standard for third-person action games in terms of length, depth, speed, and gore".<ref name="ignngrev"/> Critics also regarded it to be one of the most difficult games released prior to 2007.<ref>{{cite web |author=Danny Cowan |title=Critical Reception: Tecmo/Team Ninja's ''Ninja Gaiden Sigma'' |publisher=[[Gamasutra]] |date=2007-07-04 |url=http://previews.teamxbox.com/xbox/1143/Ninja-Gaiden-BLACK/p1/ |accessdate=2007-12-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Rob Semsey |title=''Ninja Gaiden: Black'' Hands-On |publisher=[[TeamXbox]] |date=2005-08-10 |url=http://previews.teamxbox.com/xbox/1143/Ninja-Gaiden-BLACK/p1/ |accessdate=2007-12-13 }}</ref> Its remake, ''Ninja Gaiden Black'', also impressed reviewers. GameSpot hailed it as having the best visual and audio presentation on the Xbox, and praised its new Mission Mode for "[distilling] the game down to its purest essentials".<ref name="gsngbrev"/> IGN called its release "a rare and welcome day", which "[brought their] excitement levels back to the first time [they] played the game".<ref name="ignngbrev"/>

From a technical point of view, critics regarded ''Ninja Gaiden'' and ''Black'' as the best of the available Xbox software at the time; the console hardware had been pushed to its limits without showing significant drops in performance. GameSpot was impressed with their "first-rate presentation" and said that no other games at that time came close in visuals and audio.<ref name="gsngbrev" /> According to IGN, the games could "make [them] momentarily forget about the next generation of consoles".<ref name="ignngbrev" /> Both ''Ninja Gaiden'' and ''Black'' were top-sellers, which led to them being [[backward compatibility|compatible]] with the [[Xbox 360]] for all regions on the new platform's release.<ref>{{cite news 
  | author = Tor Thorsen
  | title = 360 to play 200-plus Xbox games
  | publisher = [[GameSpot]]
  | date = 2005-11-11
  | url = http://www.gamespot.com/xbox/action/halo2/news.html?sid=6139702
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite news 
  | author = Hirohiko Niizumi
  | title = Xbox 360 backward compatibility lacking in Japan
  | publisher = [[GameSpot]]
  | date = 2005-11-16
  | url = http://www.gamespot.com/xbox/action/ninjagaidenblack/news.html?sid=6139921
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite news 
  | author = Brendan Sinclair
  | title = European 360 backward compatibility detailed
  | publisher = [[GameSpot]]
  | date = 2005-11-17
  | url = http://www.gamespot.com/xbox/action/halo2/news_6140002.html
  | accessdate = 2008-02-03 }}
</ref>

However, critics varied in their views on the technical aspects of ''Ninja Gaiden Sigma''. The gaming site, [[1UP.com]], called the updated graphics as "a gorgeous reworking of the modern ninja classic".<ref name="sig1uprev" /> [[Pro-G]], however, said that they were average by next-generation standards and showed occasional "tearing, jagged edges, and miss matched collision between bloodstains and walls".<ref name="prosigrev" /> Various flaws also troubled 1UP&mdash;despite installing the game on the local hard drive, they encountered frequent loading delays, even in combat. They also noted visual glitches, such as [[screen tearing]] when the camera moved. These problems made the game "feel like a bit of a slapdash port".<ref name="sig1uprev" /> Although reviewers appreciated the  retention of the gameplay of previous versions,<ref name="ignau" /><ref name="sig1uprev" /> ''Sigma's'' lack of new attractive features caused them to question its worth as "a remake of a remake". Pro-G said that ''Sigma'' was not worth its full-game price tag because it "has, in effect, been available for years in one form or another".<ref name="prosigrev" /> [[Eurogamer]] stated that ''Sigma'' lacked the "wow factor" when compared to ''God of War'' and [[God of War II|its sequel]].<ref name="eusigrev" /> The 1UP critic felt that shaking the Sixaxis controller to power up a ninpo was "silly" and a "foolishly tacked-on" way to use the controller.<ref name="sig1uprev" /> IGN was not excited about playing as Rachel and wished to "get back to Ryu's sections simply because he's more fun to play".<ref name="ignsigrev" /> DailyGame, however, appreciated the change of pace, saying that Rachel will bring a "much-needed respite for newcomers and provide something new for experienced players".<ref>{{cite web
  | author = Martin Ray
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Sigma Review
  | publisher = DailyGame
  | date = 2007-08-15
  | url = http://www.dailygame.net/news/archives/006499.php
  | accessdate = 2007-08-27 }}
</ref>

''Ninja Gaiden'' attracted criticism for the way on-screen action is framed by the game's camera. The default camera system centers the action on Ryu and his surroundings, but reviewers were frustrated by occasions when the camera locked on to part of the scenery, thus losing track of Ryu.<ref name="ignngbrev" /><ref name="trend" /> Tecmo attempted to address this with the introduction of manual camera controls in the ''Hurricane Packs'',<ref name="hurhands1" /><ref name="gsngbrev" />  and most critics judged that either the camera frame was usually acceptable, or that ''Ninja Gaiden'' was a good enough game that its flaws could be overlooked.<ref name="gsngbrev" /><ref name="ignsigrev" />

The ''Ninja Gaiden'' games gained a reputation throughout the gaming community for their difficulty and attention to detail.<ref name="history" /><ref>{{cite journal
  | author = Ray Huling
  | year = 2007
  | month = October
  | title = Ninja Playground
  | journal = [[The Brooklyn Rail]]
  | url = http://brooklynrail.org/2007/10/streets/ninja-playground
  | accessdate = 2007-10-12 }}
</ref> Although they appealed to gamers who, like Pro-G, wanted a "bloody hard, but also bloody good" challenge,<ref name="prongrev" /> it was feared that casual gamers would find the learning curve daunting. IGN warned that gamers with lesser skills might not "get as much out of this game as others due to [its] incredible difficulty".<ref name="ignngbrev" /> Clive Thompson focused on ''Ninja Gaiden'' in his ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' article examining the motivation for playing difficult games. He contends that extreme levels of challenge can be initially very frustrating and may cause a game to be abandoned in disgust. However, where a game also rewards a player's perseverance by teaching the skills required to overcome its challenges, that player will have the motivation to finish the game. ''Ninja Gaiden'', in his opinion, strikes the correct balance between challenge and reward; completion brings "a sort of exhausted exhilaration, like finally reaching the end of ''[[War and Peace]]''".<ref>{{cite web
  | author = Clive Thompson
  | title = Tough Love&mdash;Can a video game be too hard?
  | publisher = [[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]
  | date = 2004-05-06
  | url = http://www.slate.com/id/2100116/
  | accessdate = 2007-09-05 }}
</ref>

Consumers purchased 1.5&nbsp;million copies of ''Ninja Gaiden'' and ''Black'' to August 2007,<ref>{{cite news
  | author = Kotaro Tsunetomi
  | title = テクモが急騰、業績予想を増額－「ＮＩＮＪＡ ＧＡＩＤＥＮ」好調
  | publisher = [[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] Japan
  | date = 2007-07-06
  | url = http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=90001002&sid=azaEyzbR0k7w&refer=jp_home
  | accessdate = 2007-09-02
  | language = {{Ja icon}} }}
</ref> with the bulk of these sales going to North America and Europe. According to the [[NPD Group]], in its first month ''Ninja Gaiden'' sold 362,441&nbsp;copies in the United States, with ''Sigma'' selling 63,637.<ref>{{cite journal
  | author = NPD Tech
  | year = 2004
  | month = March
  | title = NPD US Sales Data
  | publisher = [[NPD Group]]
  | location = New York, United States
  | url = http://www.3dnews.ru/games/games-weekly-27042004/index2.htm
  | accessdate = 2008-02-03 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite journal
  | author = NPD Group
  | year = 2007
  | month = June
  | title = NPD US Sales Data
  | publisher = [[NPD Group]]
  | location = New York, United States
  | url = http://www.cubed3.com/news/8201
  | accessdate = 2008-02-03 }}
</ref> ''[[Next Generation Magazine|Next Generation]]'' reported that as of April 2008, 470,000&nbsp;copies of ''Sigma'' have been sold in Europe and North America.<ref>{{cite web
  | author = Next Generation staff
  | title = The Top 100 Selling Games of the Last 12 Months
  | publisher = ''[[Next Generation Magazine]]''
  | date = 2008-04-09
  | url = http://www.next-gen.biz/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=9639&Itemid=2
  | accessdate = 2008-04-10 }}
</ref> These sales figures reflect Tecmo's decision to target the non-Japanese market. Japanese gamers were not particularly excited by the games&mdash;according to Itagaki, only 60,000&nbsp;copies of ''Ninja Gaiden'' were sold in Japan in the four months following its release,<ref name="giint" /> and ''Famitsu'' gives a figure of 76,095&nbsp;copies for ''Sigma'' in its first six months.<ref>{{cite journal
  | author = Famitsu Marketing Data Service
  | year = January
  | month = 2008
  | title = Top 100 sales
  | journal = 2007 Yearly Report
  | publisher = [[Famitsu]]
  | location = Tokyo, Japan
  | url = http://ps3.ign.com/articles/845/845026p2.html
  | accessdate = 2008-02-03 }}
</ref> The critical and commercial successes of ''Ninja Gaiden'' have led [[CNET]] and GameSpot Asia to induct the game into their Halls of Fame.<ref>{{cite web
  | author = David Rudden
  | title = Gaming hall of fame: the Xbox's best games
  | publisher = [[CNet]]
  | date = 2006-06-16
  | url = http://reviews.cnet.com/4321-9582_7-6509238.html
  | accessdate = 2007-09-05 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | author = GameSpot Asia staff
  | title = Editor's Choice Hall of Fame
  | publisher = [[GameSpot]]
  | date = 2004-04-23
  | url = http://web.archive.org/web/20050406025443/www.gamespotasia.com/pcgames/features/story/0,2000006896,30076524,00.htm
  | accessdate = 2008-02-03 }}
</ref>
